Return the dimensions of the raster file (rows, columns and layers)

dim(new_raster)
## [1] 457 465   1

view the number of cells (pixels)

ncell(new_raster)
## [1] 212505

the raster’s spatial resolution ( a term that refers to the number of pixels utilized in construction of a digital image) The spatial extent of a data resource is a bounding box (defined by four Latitude/Longitude coordinates) and is the smallest rectangular shape which totally encloses all of the referenced data.

CRS stands for coordinate reference system

we can also explore packages such as tmap, mapview and leaflet to create interactive maps of raster and vector objects

The RasterLayer class represents the simplest form of a raster object, and consists of only one layer. The easiest way to create a raster object in R is to read-in a raster file from disk or from a server.

Create a custom raster to understand the concept

The resulting raster consists of 36 cells (6 columns and 6 rows specified by nrows and ncols). Our raster is centered around the Prime Meridian (Longitude 0) and the Equator (Latitude 0). Our raster will also be represented by random numbers, beginning from 1 to 36 to fill up the 36 cells.

new_raster2 = raster(nrows = 6, ncols = 6, res = 0.5, 
                     xmn = -1.5, xmx = 1.5, ymn = -1.5, ymx = 1.5,
                     vals = 1:36)

x-minimum, x-maximum, y-minimum, ymaximum (xmn = -1.5, xmx = 1.5, ymn = -1.5, ymx = 1.5)

You can adjust the values afterwards Plot our raster and observe the pattern (1 - 36 : the lightest colour to the brightest respectively)

plot(new_raster2)

levelplot(new_raster2)

Our plot reveals that the gradient features we see in maps are correspondent to certain figures which indicate their pixels/output.

Now, let’s try this for for Yekaterinburg (Look for Yekaterinburg from : http://srtm.csi.cgiar.org/srtmdata/)

Shuttle Radar Topography Mission (SRTM) Data SRTM data can be used to provide topography information, relief shading, and elevation profiles for trails and routes [1].

To access any country/city/area’s raster we will be working with the .TIF file type.

Visit this link below: http://srtm.csi.cgiar.org/srtmdata/ - Select the desired location (Zoom into the map for more details). - Click on the area you want to work on and search - Options: 1. Tile 5 x 5 degree 2. Geo TIFF - Search - Take a look at the metadata. - Download the SRTM file - Unzip the file and copy the .tif file into your R project folder.

I named my file ekb.tif

create an image of our raster plot

image(ekb_raster)

# specify the range of values that you want to plot in the DEM
# just plot pixels between 250 and 300 m in elevation
image(ekb_raster, zlim=c(150,300))

we can specify the colors too

col <- terrain.colors(5) #terrain.colors() tells R to create a palette of colors within the terrain.colors color ramp
image(ekb_raster, zlim=c(150,375), main="Digital Elevation Model (DEM) - Yekaterinburg", col=col)
